in irony and humor, but from then on published little. Until 1990, when her first novel, Yellow Street, was finally published, Veza was known only as her husband's muse and literary assistant. As more of her writings appeared, critics became convinced that it was he who was responsible for her decline into obscurity, notwithstanding his protestations of support and admiration. This biography tells a more nuanced story, presenting Veza's literary career against the background of her troubled times, drawing on Elias's unpublished papers to assess their literary partnership, showing how their early writings constituted a private dialogue on topics as diverse as feminism and Jewish identity and how several key themes in his work are anticipated in hers. Julian Preece is Professor of German at the University of Wales, Swansea.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aAuthors, Austriany20th centuryvBiography. 4aEnglish & American Literature. 4aGerman Literature. 4aWomen's & Gender Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / German.2bisacsh  aAvant garde.  aCensorship.  aEveryday life.  aHumor.  aIrony.  aJewish identity.  aLiterary career.  aMixed Sephardic-Ashkenazi Jewish family.  aNovelist.  aShort-story writer.  aVeza Canetti.  aVienna Arbeiter-Zeitung.  aViennese playwright.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013z978311143139040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978157113700540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781571137005423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781571137005/original  a978-3-11-143139-0  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package pre 2013b2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles